Kotlin is a lot more concise than Java, which is one of the reasons it's growing in popularity. With Kotlin, you can write code that's similar to Java, but with fewer lines and less boilerplate. For example, in Kotlin, you can create a data class like this:
```kotlin
data class Person(val name: String, val age: Int)
```
This is a lot more concise than the equivalent Java code:
```java
public class Person {
    public String name;
    public int age;

    public Person(String name, int age) {
        this.name = name;
        this.age = age;
    }
}
```
Kotlin also has a lot of other features that make it easier to write code, like extension functions and properties. For example, you can add a getter and setter to a property like this:
```kotlin
class Person {
    var name: String = ""
        get() = field
        set(value) {
            field = value
        }
}
```
This is a lot more concise than the equivalent Java code:
```java
